# Chrome Guard

Chrome Guard is a lightweight desktop tool that launches Google Chrome in a dedicated low-latency profile and monitors how the browser uses your system’s resources. It displays real-time CPU usage for Chrome’s processes, highlights heavy tab renderers, and logs alerts when usage stays above thresholds.

A simple Tkinter UI lets you open Chrome directly from the app and watch live metrics.

## Features

* Launches Chrome with an isolated performance profile
* Tracks total Chrome CPU usage and highest individual process
* Shows per-tab CPU estimates using the Chrome DevTools Protocol
* Displays live CPU meters in a desktop UI
* Logs alerts when CPU usage stays high for multiple intervals

## Project Layout

```
chrome-guard/
    README.md
    requirements.txt

    chrome_guard/
        __init__.py
        config.py
        launcher.py
        monitor.py
        notifications.py
        ui.py
        utils/
            __init__.py
            process_utils.py
            gpu_utils.py

    scripts/
        run_gui.py
        run_monitor_only.py
```

## Installation

```
python3 -m venv .venv
source .venv/bin/activate
pip install -r requirements.txt
```

## Running the App

### Launch the UI

```
python3 scripts/run_gui.py
```

This opens the Tkinter interface where you can enter a URL and view live metrics.

### Monitor Only

```
python3 scripts/run_monitor_only.py
```

Prints Chrome CPU metrics to the terminal without the UI.

## Configuration

You can override defaults through environment variables:

```
CHROME_GUARD_CHROME_PATH
CHROME_GUARD_CPU_TOTAL
CHROME_GUARD_CPU_SINGLE
CHROME_GUARD_POLL_INTERVAL
CHROME_GUARD_SUSTAINED_HITS
```

Defaults are set in `config.py`.
